04700nam a22006735i 9780231551267DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021027100  a97802315512677 a10.7312/gart195242doi  a(DE-B1597)635312  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV6433.M5 4aHV6433.M5bG38 2022 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a363.32509562231 aGartenstein-Ross, Daveed, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnemies Near and Far :bHow Jihadist Groups Strategize, Plot, and Learn /cDaveed Gartenstein-Ross, Thomas Joscelyn. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Terrorism and Irregular Warfare00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 The Fire Next Time -- t2 Learning to Win -- t3 The Far- Enemy Strategy -- t4 The Unfriendly Skies: Plots Against Aviation -- t5 The Early Adopter: Anwar al- Awlaki in the Digital Space -- t6 Strategic Learning: Al- Qaeda and Jihadism in the Arab Spring -- t7 The Islamic State’s Rise and Rule -- t8 The Fitna: ISIS Versus al- Qaeda -- t9 How al- Qaeda Survived the War in Afghanistan -- t10 ISIS’s External Operations: A Study in Innovation -- t11 The Past and Future of Jihadist Organizational Learning -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the United States has prioritized its fight against militant groups for two decades, the transnational jihadist movement has proved surprisingly resilient and adaptable. Many analysts and practitioners have underestimated these militant organizations, viewing them as unsophisticated or unchanging despite the ongoing evolution of their tactics and strategies.In Enemies Near and Far, two internationally recognized experts use newly available documents from al-Qaeda and ISIS to explain how jihadist groups think, grow, and adapt. Daveed Gartenstein-Ross and Thomas Joscelyn recast militant groups as learning organizations, detailing their embrace of strategic, tactical, and technological innovation. Drawing on theories of organizational learning, they provide a sweeping account of these groups’ experimentation over time. Gartenstein-Ross and Joscelyn shed light on militant groups’ most effective strategic and tactical moves, including attacks targeting aircraft and the use of the internet to inspire and direct lone attackers, and they examine jihadists’ ability to shift their strategy based on political context. While militant groups’ initial efforts to upgrade their capabilities often fail, these attempts should generally be understood not as failures but as experiments in service of a learning process—a process that continues until these groups achieve a breakthrough.Providing unprecedented historical and strategic perspective on how jihadist groups learn and evolve, Enemies Near and Far also explores how to anticipate future threats, analyzing how militants are likely to deploy a range of emerging technologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aInsurgencyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aJihadxHistoryy21st century. 0aOrganizational learningzMiddle EastxHistoryy21st century. 0aTerrorismzMiddle EastxHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh1 aJoscelyn, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/gart1952440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231551267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231551267/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13E